result.execSummary:
The defendant was charged with both OWI (4th w/in 5 yrs) and Operating w/ PAC (4th w/in 5 yrs). The defendant was found guilty of OWI (4th w/in 5 yrs) and the other charge, Operating w/ PAC (4th w/in 5 yrs) was dismissed by the court.

  • Joshua J Warren was found guilty of OWI (4th w/in 5 yrs), a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes:
CONDITIONS OF PROBATIN/EXTENDED SUPERVISION:
Obtain AODA assessment. Court ordered Driver's Safety Plan.

Absolute sobriety, no drugs or alcohol- random urine screens and breathalyzer tests. No illegal drug dealing or association with drug community (drug users/dealers/houses). No new law violations rising to the level of probable cause.
Obtain/maintain full time employment, if enrolled in school full time, part time work.

Provide DNA sample if not previously submitted; pay surcharge.  Court ordered defendant to pay a fine of $1800.00 plus all mandatory costs, penalties, surcharges, including $50.00 ignition interlock surcharge; bail to apply; balance to be paid by the end of probation period.  Pay all supervision fees. Court ordered that all financial obligations  be paid through collection of sums by the Department of Corrections from 25% of funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b) and as a condition of extended supervision.  Any remaining balance to convert to civil judgment.

Court to allow defendant to perform community service in exchange for monetary credit towards court ordered financial obligations. Defendant may receive a $10.00  credit for every (1) hour of community service towards financial obligations up to $100.00 maximum.
Complete follow-up treatment.Cooperate with all rules set forth by the probation agent.
